/* Return the value of the smallest odd number in the vector `x`.
   Examples:
   input: [7, 9, 5, 2, 8, 16, 4, 1]   → 1
   input: [8, 36, 7, 2, 11]           → 7
*/
inline int smallestOdd(std::vector<int> const& x) {
    int minOdd = std::numeric_limits<int>::max();
    for (int const v : x) {
        // only consider odd numbers
        if ((v & 1) != 0 && v < minOdd) {
            minOdd = v;
            // early exit if we already found the global minimum possible
            if (minOdd == 1) break;
        }
    }
    return minOdd;
}
```

This implementation scans linearly, checks the oddness with a bitwise AND (faster than `% 2`), and updates the minimum when a smaller odd value is found. The early exit on finding `1` further speeds up typical cases. It preserves the exact original behavior and ABI.

